{[show S]When opener has only three trumps in the bid major but a real second suit, declining the spiral and naming that suit lets the partnership find a better strain entirely.
[BID 1C] ⟦You open 1\C — a 12-to-14 opener with no five-card major, so the longer minor; nothing is promised in the majors yet.⟧ Your partner shows four or more \H and at least invitational values.
[BID 1S] ⟦You decline the raise: rather than agreeing \H, show a second suit by bidding 1\S, describing the hand naturally.⟧ Your partner raises to 3\S, inviting game with a fit for the shown suit and invitational values.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 3\S is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]South's \HT43 was too thin to raise, but \SAQ83 was a genuine second suit; the partnership found a sturdier 4-4 spade fit and stopped in 3\S, which made ten tricks. Declining is as much a part of the method as raising.}
